i. For the bookmaker “bet-at-home” Initial Empirical and Probabilistic value

Figure 11: Initial Empirical and Probabilistic Value of the bookmaker “bet-at-home”

  • What i want to expect is to see probabilistic over and empirical over as much as close to each other. In other words, as the distance between them is getting less, the level of predicting quality increased for this bookmaker.

  • For instance, for the range “(0.2,0.4]”, namely in the first graph, in 2014 the gap is so much. The bookmaker did not determine own values right. Then, the gap is a bit reduced over the years. However, the gap is beginning to increase after 2016. In 2018, the empirical value is 0.52 and the probabilistic value is 0.37. The points that i mentioned are on the first graph’s last extreme points as you see. The bookmaker prediction is higher than probabilistic value. For the first range’s fluctuation is so much. But the fluctuation is not because of the bookmaker’s prediction. Actually, in reality the results are fluctuated. Yet, the fluctuation was not taken into account by the bookmaker when the bookmaker determines own prediction.Therefore the distance between these values are quite much.For the range “(0.4,0.6]” and the year “2018”, the gap between these values are getting less.

  • For the range “(0.4,0.6]”, namely in the second graph, in 2011 the gap between these values are a bit far from each other. After 2012 the values are quite close to each other, which represents the quality of prediction of the bookmaker. Although in 2016 the gap was increased, then it began decreasing.

  • For the range “(0.6,0.8]”, namely in the third graph, in 2011 the gap between these values are a bit far from each other. After 2012 the values are quite close to each other, which represents the quality of prediction of the bookmaker. Although in 2015 the gap was increased, then it began decreasing. The bookmaker determining the probabilstic value does not want to take a risk. Since the blue line for each range plot is not so considerably low or high.

  1. Home win Situation

Figure 13: Initial and Final Probability of Home Win for the bookmaker “Pinnacle”

  • The first graph represents the initial and final probability of home win. X axes is year, which is independent variable. y axes is Probability of home win, which is dependent variable. You can view the initial and final probabilities of the bookmaker “Pinnacle”. As can be seen on the graph, in 2010 the difference between initial and final probabilites determined by the bookmaker “Pinnacle” is quite high when i compared to the other years’ gap. In other words, in advance the bookmaker “Pinnacle” is not very consistent determining the probabilities. This bookmaker changed the probabilities at a significant rate in 2010. But then, especially after 2012, the gap reduced considerably as you can observe. Even from 2013 to 2017, the gap between initial and final probability of home win is almost zero. In 2018 the gap between final and initial probability of home win increases. Namely, the level of inconsistency between initial and final values goes up. Generally, when i observe this plot, i can say that the bookmaker is getting consistent over the years.

a)Appendix1:First Task:Option a

i. Codes of Section i

matches=unique(matches)

matches[ ,match_date := anydate(date)]

matches[ ,match_time := anytime(date)]

matches[,c(“HomeGoals”,“AwayGoals”):=tstrsplit(score,‘:’)]

matches=matches[complete.cases(matches)]

matches[,c(“HomeGoals”,“AwayGoals”):=tstrsplit(score,‘:’)]

matches[,HomeGoals:=as.numeric(HomeGoals)]

matches[,AwayGoals:=as.numeric(AwayGoals)]

matches[,TotalGoals:=HomeGoals+AwayGoals]

matches[,IsOver:=0]

matches[TotalGoals>2,IsOver:=1]

odds=unique(odds)

odds[ ,match_date := anydate(date)]

odds[ ,match_time := anytime(date)]

odds_ov_un=odds[betType==‘ou’ & totalhandicap==‘2.5’]

odds_ov_un[,totalhandicap:=NULL]

odds_ov_un=odds_ov_un[order(matchId, oddtype,bookmaker,date)]

odds_ov_un_initial=odds_ov_un[,list(start_odd=odd[1]), by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]

odds_ov_un_final=odds_ov_un[,list(final_odd=odd[.N]),by=list(matchId,oddtype,bookmaker)]

odds=odds[complete.cases(odds)]

wide_odds_initial=dcast(odds_ov_un_initial,matchId~oddtype+bookmaker,value.var=‘start_odd’)

Pinnacle_over_under_initial=odds_ov_un_initial[bookmaker==‘Pinnacle’]

Pinnacle_wide_initial=dcast(Pinnacle_over_under_initial,matchId~oddtype,value.var=‘start_odd’)

matches[,Year:=year(match_time)]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle=merge(matches,Pinnacle_wide_initial,by=‘matchId’)

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,probOver:=1/over]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,probUnder:=1/under]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,totalProb:=probOver+probUnder]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,probOver:=probOver/totalProb]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,probUnder:=probUnder/totalProb]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle=merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[complete.cases(merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle)]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,totalProb:=NULL]

cutpoints=seq(0,1,0.1)

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,odd_cut_over:=cut(probOver,cutpoints)]

merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,odd_cut_under:=cut(probUnder,cutpoints)]

summary_table_initial_Pinnacle=merged_matches_initial_Pinnacle[,list(empirical_over=mean(IsOver),probabilistic_over=mean(probOver),.N),by=list(Year,odd_cut_over)]

summary_table_initial_Pinnacle=summary_table_initial_Pinnacle[order(Year)]

plot(summary_table_initial_Pinnacle[,list(empirical_over,probabilistic_over)],cex=4,main=“Compare Empirical value to Probabilistic value for Pinnacle Initial”)

abline(0,1,col=‘red’)
